<HEADLINE>
<P>
HAHN URGES MORE POOL INSPECTIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Supervisor Kenneth Hahn said Tuesday that Los Angeles County's 16,700 public 
pools ought to be inspected at least once a year, even if annual pool licensing 
fees have to be raised to hire more inspectors. 
</P>
<P>
Hahn issued a press release two days after The Times reported that the county 
has just eight pool inspectors -- the same number as it had 20 years ago when 
there were half as many public pools. 
</P>
<P>
Forty-one percent of the public pools in the county have not been inspected for 
at least three years; almost 5,000 pools have not been inspected for at least 
four years. 
</P>
<P>
Hahn said he will introduce a motion at Tuesday's board meeting calling for 
county staff to prepare a report by Oct. 16 on the situation, including 
recommendations for fee increases. 
</P>
<P>
"Unsafe conditions at any county facility cannot be tolerated and every effort 
must be made to ensure public safety," Hahn said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
