<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
North American-Made Vehicle Sales Drop: Sales of cars and trucks dropped 5.6% 
in mid-September, compared to last year, when high inventories pressed auto 
makers to offer big incentives, the companies said. A 42.3% increase in the 
sales of cars made in North America by Japanese companies was offset by a 7.5% 
decline in cars made by General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. 
The Big Three held 84.4% of the car market in mid-September. 
</P>
<P>
The 10 major companies making cars and trucks in the U.S. said they sold 
vehicles at an average daily rate of 35,810 during the Sept. 11-20 period this 
year, compared to a rate of 37,948 a year earlier year. Car sales were down 
2.6%, and truck sales were off 10.5%. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
