September 26, 1990, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<P>
DAVID KIRKPATRICK 
</P>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 7; Column 2; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
157 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE: DAVID KIRKPATRICK NAMED PARAMOUNT CO-PRESIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NINA J. EASTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paramount Pictures confirmed Tuesday that David Kirkpatrick will become the 
next co-president of its motion picture group, replacing Sidney Ganis. 
</P>
<P>
The change, which ends weeks of speculation about the future of the two 
executives, is effective immediately. 
</P>
<P>
Ganis will become an independent producer with a long-term agreement at 
Paramount. In a prepared statement, Ganis -- who spent most of his career 
marketing movies -- called production "a longtime commitment of mine" and said 
Paramount is the "best home base for the kinds of films I look forward to 
making." 
</P>
<P>
Kirkpatrick, who joined Paramount from Disney in July, will report directly to 
studio Chairman Frank Mancuso. Barry London, the co-president responsible for 
marketing and distribution, will remain in his position, studio officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Ganis had been president of the motion picture group, overseeing feature film 
production, since November, 1988. NINA J. EASTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
