<P>
101-CARAT DIAMOND UP FOR SALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
GENEVA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The largest internally flawless diamond to be auctioned will be put on sale in 
Geneva on Nov. 14. 
</P>
<P>
David Bennett, director of Sotheby's jewelry department, told a news conference 
today that the 101.84-carat stone could fetch about $13 million. 
</P>
<P>
The pear-shaped stone is 1.43 inches long and was certified by the Gemological 
Institute of America as D color. In a white diamond, this is the highest 
possible classification, denoting a total absence of color. "It is an extremely 
rare feature in a diamond of this size," Bennett said. 
</P>
<P>
It also has a purity grading known as "internally flawless," which is important 
because the presence of inclusions or other natural features within a stone can 
impair its brilliance. 
</P>
